## Known Findings (do not duplicate)

- F-001: Reward accounting mixes deposit amounts with LP shares, enabling reward theft and claim lockups (High, high)
- F-002: LP shares are minted from `tokenAmount + ethAmount`, so inventory shifts can overmint shares and drain the scarcer asset (High, high)
- F-003: Deposits use manipulable Uniswap spot reserves instead of the pool's own balances (High, medium)
- F-004: Fee-on-transfer or deflationary tokens are over-credited, creating unbacked LP balances (High, high)
- F-006: Small deposits can mint zero LP shares and become permanently stuck (Medium, high)
- F-007: Rebasing or confiscatory tokens can desynchronize accounting and lock LP exits (Medium, medium)
- F-010: Existing pools can be bricked or mispriced because pair checks use the current router, not the stored pair (Medium, high)
- F-011: Reward payouts are not isolated per pool, so one undercollateralized reward bucket can drain unrelated pools (Medium, high)
- F-014: Reward deposits are stranded when a pool keeps liquidity after total LP shares fall to zero (Low, medium)
- F-015: Blocking a token freezes the orderbook repayment path while the pool can still accept fresh liquidity (Medium, medium)
- F-017: Orderbook settlement cannot repay assets after draining a pool's tracked liquidity to zero (Medium, high)
- F-018: Owner emergency withdrawals can seize all LP principal and leave pools permanently insolvent (High, high)
- F-019: New LPs can dilute and steal outstanding orderbook receivables (High, high)
- F-020: Full withdrawals hard-require a successful ETH reward payout, which can trap remaining principal (Medium, high)
- F-021: Small fee distributions are permanently stranded because reward dust is never carried forward (Low, high)
- F-023: Changing the registry or orderbook can strand assets already borrowed by the previous orderbook (Medium, high)
- F-103: The first depositor after a zero-share state can seize stranded pool assets and later orderbook repayments (High, medium)
- F-024: Orderbook loans are not isolated per pool, so repayments can be redirected to a different pool (High, high)

